{
  "texts": [
    "To address this, we here propose relying on moving horizon estimation (MHE) [22].",
    "As a moving-horizon and optimization-based observer method, MHE is a natural counterpart for MPC controllers, allowing the use of the same MPC prediction model for state estimation.",
    "In particular, in our setting, MHE allows us to embed the data-based model of each ensemble component in the observer scheme.",
    "Furthermore, state constraints can be handled explicitly.For a prediction horizon Ĥ, at each time instant t = kτ, with k ∈ N, the following MHE problem, a function of the previous Ĥ applied inputs and measured outputs, u ∈ R nu× Ĥ and y p ∈ R ny× Ĥ, is solved for each model in the ensemble, according to the receding horizon strategy:P [i] MHE x[i], u, y p = min x[i],ω [i],ν [i] x[i] (k -Ĥ) -x[i] Qx + k-1 h=k-Ĥ ν [i] (h) Qν + ω [i] (h) Qω (8a) s.t.",
    "∀h ∈ {k -Ĥ,..., k -1} x[i] (h + 1) = f [i] x[i] (h), u(h) + ω [i] (h),(8b)y p (h) = g [i] x[i] (h), u(h) + ν [i] (h),(8c)x[i] (h) ∈ X,(8d)where ω [i] and ν [i] are the process and measurement error, with the matrices Q ω and Q ν weighting their penalties, respectively."
  ]
}